subject: WIP Simple Cache Service
revisions:
[{'number': 2, 'created': '2016-03-02 00:24:32.000000000', 'files': ['horizon/static/framework/util/cache/cache.service.js', 'horizon/static/framework/util/cache/cache.service.spec.js', 'horizon/static/framework/util/cache/cache.module.js', 'horizon/static/framework/util/util.module.js'], 'message': 'WIP Simple Cache Service

When a user takes action on a resource, a view may not have the
updated item for a few seconds, however it is important
that the UI remember that the item is "in-progress" so that it can
give a visual clue to the user that their action had an effect.

This simple cache service is intended to be used like this:
1) View offers an action on an item.
2) User clicks action
3) Immediately when action returns, view "adds" the item to the cache
   with a timestamp that indicates when the resource was last updated.
   This timestamp may be server time, or client time, depending on the
   needs of the view.
4) The view can use "inCache" for each item to decide if the item needs
   to be marked as "in-progress" for the user.  Any item that is in
   the cache may be inconsistent with the service side until the next
   "sync"
5) When the view next gets a full list of resource items (perhaps from
   polling) it calls cache "sync" on each item with the appropriate
   timestamp for each newly fetched item (again, possibly using server
   time for the most recent fetch).

   If "sync" finds the item in the cache with a newer timestamp, it
   returns it. This means the client hasn't gotten an updated version
   since the user's action.

   If "sync" finds the item in the cache, but it has an older timestamp
   the new item is preferred, and the old item is cleared from the cache.

   In both cases, the caller should always use the item returned by "sync"
   so that the cache can substitute cached items when necessary.
6) Periodically, call "clean" to clean out items older than some
   maximum age (perhaps 2X the polling period).
   
   NOTE: The "age" of an item in the cache is the client time differnce
   from when it was added. The 'timestamp' on the other hand, is a value
   that indicates when the item was last fetched from the service and
   may be server time, client time, or some other counter.

Change-Id: I9b45df6ca84411544b287322c6002c4cec249543
Partially-Implements: blueprint searchlight-search-panel
'}]
commit_message:
WIP Simple Cache Service

When a user takes action on a resource, a view may not have the
updated item for a few seconds, however it is important
that the UI remember that the item is "in-progress" so that it can
give a visual clue to the user that their action had an effect.

This simple cache service is intended to be used like this:
1) View offers an action on an item.
2) User clicks action
3) Immediately when action returns, view "adds" the item to the cache
   with a timestamp that indicates when the resource was last updated.
   This timestamp may be server time, or client time, depending on the
   needs of the view.
4) The view can use "inCache" for each item to decide if the item needs
   to be marked as "in-progress" for the user.  Any item that is in
   the cache may be inconsistent with the service side until the next
   "sync"
5) When the view next gets a full list of resource items (perhaps from
   polling) it calls cache "sync" on each item with the appropriate
   timestamp for each newly fetched item (again, possibly using server
   time for the most recent fetch).

   If "sync" finds the item in the cache with a newer timestamp, it
   returns it. This means the client hasn't gotten an updated version
   since the user's action.

   If "sync" finds the item in the cache, but it has an older timestamp
   the new item is preferred, and the old item is cleared from the cache.

   In both cases, the caller should always use the item returned by "sync"
   so that the cache can substitute cached items when necessary.
6) Periodically, call "clean" to clean out items older than some
   maximum age (perhaps 2X the polling period).
   
   NOTE: The "age" of an item in the cache is the client time differnce
   from when it was added. The 'timestamp' on the other hand, is a value
   that indicates when the item was last fetched from the service and
   may be server time, client time, or some other counter.

Change-Id: I9b45df6ca84411544b287322c6002c4cec249543
Partially-Implements: blueprint searchlight-search-panel

commit_message:
Generate Javascript API docs

This patch adds jsdoc to our development dependencies
and invokes it when documentation is built. To just generate
the Javascript API docs, run "./run_tests.sh --jsdoc".

The tox job was modified to use the run_tests.sh --docs
command so that the Javascript docs are included in the docs
build.

commit_message:
Fix alignment issue in project table inline edit

Click the inline edit pencil icon in "Enabled" cell of the
project table in identity project panel, you will see the
checkbox and the label not align well. This issue will
affect later table inline edit. We can use the css class
"checkbox" in bootstrap to fix this bug.

The labels "Active Instances" and "Active RAM" in the Project Overview tab
leads to user misunderstanding about the information it shows. Users can
be induced to think that "Active Instances" is the number of instances that
is currently running on the project, but it shows the number of instances that
are in use (running, shutted-off or suspended).

To prevent this misunderstanding, I changed added a new header in that section
with clear indication of the dates the summary is related to; and changed the
text from "Active Instances" and "Active RAM" to "Instances in Use" and "RAM

Closes-Bug: #1286286
'}]
commit_message:
Clarifying Project Overview usage labels

The labels "Active Instances" and "Active RAM" in the Project Overview tab
leads to user misunderstanding about the information it shows. Users can
be induced to think that "Active Instances" is the number of instances that
is currently running on the project, but it shows the number of instances that
are in use (running, shutted-off or suspended).

To prevent this misunderstanding, I changed added a new header in that section
with clear indication of the dates the summary is related to; and changed the
text from "Active Instances" and "Active RAM" to "Instances in Use" and "RAM
in Use" for the sake of a clarity.

Change-Id: I3cb6f59879dce2790a4605e21403c8705d1ea330
Closes-Bug: #1286286

commit_message:
Add kernel and ramdisk setted in editing an image

1.Create an image via UI (don't set Kernel and Ramdisk)
2.Edit image , try to set kernel or/and ramdisk
Actual results:
kernel and ramdisk fields are disabled
Expected results:
kernel and ramdisk were successfully set

commit_message:
TableTab now honors Table permissions

When defining a TableTab we specify one or more DataTable via
table_classes attribute.
This fix checks DataTable permissions and doesn't render a table
if a user has not the right permissions.

Change-Id: I71164fab7f9bcbc4e37560f9dfa1859d147353d7
Closes-Bug: #1431049

the view takes action with the acted upon items (deleting them from
the table in this case...but in general all it would know is that
the item is "in-progress" and a data refresh may be needed.

commit_message:
WIP Proof of concept for actions returning promises

This is a test of actions returning a standard promise to allow
a view to act on arbitrary actions without knowledge of the meaning
of that action...or what kind of interface the action uses.

It can then tell which items were successfully acted upon. In cases
where the action doesn't return the updated data...the view can
simply indicate the item is "in-progress" and  will be updated
whenever the view chooses to refresh its list of data)

This now modified the "actions" directive to allow the view controller
to pass a promise handler that the action should return the promise
to.

To use:
1) Create an image as an admin.
2) Go to /project/ngimages
3) Select an image (or set of images) to delete. You can select
   a mix of images that you are allowed, or not, to delete.
4) Hit the "Delete Images" button.
5) The console logs the action result and the image is removed from
   the table

Notice that the view doesn't need to know that the user just clicked
a "delete" action. Instead, the action returns a standard promise,
with standard data, that the view can use to update "created",
"deleted", "updated" or "failed" items. This allows the view to be
able to handle almost any future action available for images, with no
additional changes.

Notice also that the event dispatched by the delete image action is no
longer used by the view, instead, when the modal resolves its promise
the view takes action with the acted upon items (deleting them from
the table in this case...but in general all it would know is that
the item is "in-progress" and a data refresh may be needed.

Change-Id: I715e6b8f8b906ffe91d4ee4be89c3f0d285f713b
Partially-Implements: blueprint searchlight-search-panel

commit_message:
Add horizon support for multi-attached volumes

- Improve the formatting of the Attached To column in the Volumes table
  when a volume is attached to more than one host.
- Modify the Edit Volume Attachments dialog to permit attaching
  multiattach volumes to more than one instance
- Add multiattach checkbox to create volume dialog
- Add multiattach column in volume table
- Disallow Detach table action in manage attachments dialog

Partially implements blueprint: cinder-multi-attach-volume
Change-Id: I1e6e3521ba45ac61b5e39b9b6d5e7e4ab4ef9803

commit_message:
Show datastores and versions for Trove

Add a new "datastores" panel to Trove dashboard.

IndexView displays a list of datastores with a link to DetailView for
each datastore.

DetailView displays two tabs: overview and versions.
Overview tab shows basic information.
Versions tab shows a table with data about versions. Somes columns are
only visible to admin (namely: active, packages, image ID).

Change-Id: Ie380205d90457760097ada7d121d3b25a2c89444
Implements: blueprint trove-list-datastores-and-versions

commit_message:
Subnet Delete Action

Adds a very basic subnet delete action. It can be tested using the
parent patch "resource browser".

Of particular interest is the new proposed structure to hold
resource related actions and views. Resource types follow the heat
specification. In this case, the type is "OS::Neutron::Subnet".

I propose a similar directory structure:
 * app/core/resource - indicates resource related code (as opposed to
	widgets or utilities
 * app/core/resource/os-neutron-subnet - the particular resource
	following the Heat naming convention.
 * app/core/resource/os-neutron-subnet/actions - actions specific
	to OS::Neutron::Subnet

If Openstack-wide, or Neutron-wide actions or views are
desired, they can be placed in app/core/resource/os, or
app/core/resource/os-neutron.

Change-Id: Ie845726dfd8303dfcafc69fd2340b9c29289bd37

commit_message:
WIP Developer panel to allow testing of resource actions

This creates a debug only "developer" panel that enumerates all
registered resource types and any actions associated with them.

It allows for testing of Angular-based resource actions when
an Angular version of the overview page for that resource doesn't
exist.

To test, enable ngimages (_1051_project_ngimages)

Change-Id: Ibb0126dde864767fd7e2414d53f0058f011eb028

revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-03-09 02:13:10.000000000', 'files': ['.eslintrc'], 'message': 'Turn off JSDoc linting

We do not currently generate documentation using JSDoc. A lot of
our documentation attempts to follow ngdoc rules (but often fails).

We should most likely be using Sphinx for our Javascript documentation

that can be published to docs.openstack.org

commit_message:
Turn off JSDoc linting

We do not currently generate documentation using JSDoc. A lot of
our documentation attempts to follow ngdoc rules (but often fails).

We should most likely be using Sphinx for our Javascript documentation
anyway, since that will allow us to generate integrated documentation
that can be published to docs.openstack.org

Turning off JSDoc linting removes around 85% of our lint warnings.

Change-Id: I33a4b62dc7651d62e1f0ef0b053b9c502c414313
Partial-Bug: 1554824

commit_message:
Add tests for verification of NameSpace visibility for associated resource

Actions::
 - Import new sample namespace
 - Have it not be associated to any resource type
 - Go to images --> Update Metadata
 - Verify that the namespace is not shown
 - Go back to namespaces page and associate it with OS::Glance::Image
 - Go back to images --> Update metadata
 - Verify that the namespace is now shown

Implements blueprint: horizon-integration-tests-coverage
Change-Id: I3eb296c09963f4fe0e23e555068aefecdd243d0d

commit_message:
Confirm Dialog for Delete operation in Network Topology

When we click a delete button in network topology, the corresponding
delete operation is issued immediately. Now, a confirm dialog is
displayed first to confirm the user's action and then the item gets
deleted accordingly. It brings better consistency with delete
operations of other tables.

Co-Authored-By: Allen <chen.qiaomin@99cloud.net>

Change-Id: Ib0526a8a307f053886d55b61942cc5131bd924d0
Closes-Bug: #1242251

commit_message:
WIP Network Configuration

Adds new panel to guide the administrator through creating an external network
and then set up private networks per project for them.

To bring up UI panels, go to url:
/project/networks/network_configuration/create/

Not ready for review:
 UI Panels only no logic
 needs cleanup, descriptions, re-organizing,
 includes files that other patches will be committing which will be removed
 includes depenedencies that will also be removed

Change-Id: Ia8924c904cb825998f835aec4119b85bf87621f3
Implements: blueprint admin-network-configuration

commit_message:
Support of rescue instance in Horizon

If the instance is went to error or access failure
status, the user can rescue the instance and access
the file system via the 'nova rescue' command.
This support is added in the horizon, now the user
can rescue the instance via horizon. 'Rescue Instance'
option will be available in row action. once the
instance is rescued the 'UnRescue Instance'
option will be shown in the row action.
User can come out from the rescue mode by clicking the
'UnRescue Instance' option.

Change-Id: I844c86c95aae6426514fe6220ece5b2100aa95bc
Implements: blueprint instance-rescue-horizon-support
Co-Authored-By: Cédric Soulas <cedric.soulas@cloudwatt.com>

commit_message:
Added tests for check instance row actions functionality

Tests check that instance soft reboot, create snapshot, resize, associate/
disassociate floating ip, edit name and security groups actions are executed
without errors under regular user (Project > Compute > Instances page) and
only instance soft reboot action - under admin (Admin > System > Instances
page).

Implements blueprint: horizon-integration-tests-coverage

commit_message:
Add hostname validation for create instance

Horizon does not have hostname validation in instance creation form. For
example, you can create a new instance with name: "#3rtttt".

That name will cause problems when Nova try to handle, but Horizon allow
launch a new instance with a not valid hostname. A valid hostname is
specified in RFC1123 (http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1123).

Change-Id: Ifd10c621d3f2bd3f969c7a51b3ec9bf2a0c0a8e0
Closes-bug: #1458800

revisions:
[{'number': 3, 'created': '2016-04-08 22:27:22.000000000', 'files': ['openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/volumes/cgroups/tables.py', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/volumes/cgroups/tests.py', 'openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/volumes/cgroups/workflows.py'], 'message': 'Volume consistency groups underscore issue

Volumes and volume types that contain an underscore are not
properly handled in the volume consistency group create
and update forms, which are Horizon workflows.

Underlying JS in the workflow appears to be using underscores
as a delimiter to fetch the item name, which results in the
workflow not returning the correct items.

A solution to this issue is to use IDs instead of names
when populating the tables in the workflow panels.

Change-Id: I5dc115c956a2eda4a9505b245282ef50f3dc19cf
Closes-Bug: #1566918
'}]
commit_message:
Volume consistency groups underscore issue

Volumes and volume types that contain an underscore are not
properly handled in the volume consistency group create
and update forms, which are Horizon workflows.

Underlying JS in the workflow appears to be using underscores
as a delimiter to fetch the item name, which results in the
workflow not returning the correct items.

A solution to this issue is to use IDs instead of names
when populating the tables in the workflow panels.

Change-Id: I5dc115c956a2eda4a9505b245282ef50f3dc19cf
Closes-Bug: #1566918

commit_message:
Refactor openstack_dashboard tabs.py code

In most tabs.py table of openstack dashboard apps,
we used hardcode for Tab name and slug which we
had defined them in related tables Meta, we could
use table meta directly.
It has been partially fixed in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/196341/

commit_message:
Fix out of scope comprehension iteration variable

*replace the comprehension iteration variable with vip_fips[0]
*so that it will work in python 3
*Previously, if there were multiple floating IPs,
*then only the first would be removed,
*but the message would report that the last had been removed.

Change-Id: Ic4460cac024729bc608f5d8d0567fb340caa8bc2
Closes-Bug: #1575589

commit_message:
Add tests for modification of Resource Types for NameSpaces.

Actions:
1) Create new NameSpace.
2) For NameSpace press 'Update Associations'
3) In 'NameSpace Resource Type Associations' form select all
   available types and fill the Prefix for all with unique values.
   Then submit changes.
4) In table with NameSpaces check that assigned 'Resource Types'
   were actually assigned to your NameSpace.
5) Click on NameSpace name to open details page.
6) Check that prefix was set correctly for appropriate resource.
7) Go back to 'Metadata Definitions' page and delete NameSpace.

Implements blueprint: horizon-integration-tests-coverage
Change-Id: I4e9e8e5d7de7f8dd72466ea3ac350920497290a1

Refactored iframe_embed_settings

This patch moves iframe_embed_settings template tag from context_selection

context_selection. That should carry only template tags used in
context_selection section.

commit_message:
Enforce limits on metadata tree items

This patch adds support to the metadata-tree directive for enforcing
a maximum number of metadata items that can be added, and also a
maximum length for string metadata values and a maximum length for
custom key names.

The metadata tree items display a message when the key or value
exceeds the maximum length. When the max item count is exceeded a
message is displayed above the metadata tree and the border of the
existing metadata list is changed to use the $brand-danger color.

The metadata modal is updated so that a max key length of 255 is
enforced and a max value length of 255 is enforced for all but image
metadata. Image metadata values do not have limits. For instances and
images, the max item count is obtained from the nova limits
(maxServerMeta, maxImageMeta). For aggregates and flavors there is no
max item count.

Closes-Bug: #1548510
Change-Id: I9da9ac3bcf520256fde7d25c65686334defc055f

commit_message:
Hide the flavor which disk is smaller than the old one

When we resize a vm, and select a flavor which disk is smaller than old one,
The nova-compute will raise a error:
ERROR oslo_messaging.rpc.dispatcher ResizeError: Resize error:
Unable to resize disk down.

So we should hide the flavor which disk is smaller than the old one

Change-Id: Iaad30735d2de8ca3a8d01e0318c302af6d799513
Closes-Bug: #1582081

commit_message:
Add Support For Required Architecture Metadata

Adds support for a OPENSTACK_IMAGE_BACKEND['image_architectures'] array in
horizon settings which defines a set of architecture choices which are
required to be supplied for image creation.  This supports the use case
where image architecture meta data is used to schedule images onto a
specific host aggregate in heterogenous clouds.  This change is backwards
compatible with previous releases in that if the setting is not specified
the optional text field is displayed.

Closes-Bug: 1519720

Change-Id: I71e7f9e4b21b9bbf2da23b6ebb1eb94efb06687d

commit_message:
[DO NOT MERGE] Basic Angular Schema Form POC

Consider this a very basic example of schema-form usage. The basic idea
is to use a controller as a view model, and then reuse a generic modal
template. Using this design, all modals, forms, form fields, even
validation messages can be standardised across every single
form/workflow/modal. This is a very big improvement on manually writing
out the HTML for these items.

TODO:
- Work out how to fit help-panel into this
- Decide on a generic way to handle submit (ctrl.submit etc)

Possible Future improvements:
- Map commonly used form items, like transfer tables, to a schema form
  type like array (they serve similar purposes, so maybe thats what
  should be replaced)

Change-Id: I257b3f445ffd08311f15699cc34ceed6aecfdfd6

When cluster creation fails due to an operation timeout, the cluster
status_description is set to something not so useful:

  Creating cluster failed for the following reason(s):
  'Operation' timed out after 300 second(s)

Which doesn't provide much actionable information. This change adds
the function and command to the message, so:

  Creating cluster failed for the following reason(s):
  'Operation with name '_execute_command: service ambari-server start''
  timed out after 300 second(s)

commit_message:
Improve timeout message when cluster create fails

When cluster creation fails due to an operation timeout, the cluster
status_description is set to something not so useful:

  Creating cluster failed for the following reason(s):
  'Operation' timed out after 300 second(s)

Which doesn't provide much actionable information. This change adds
the function and command to the message, so:

  Creating cluster failed for the following reason(s):
  'Operation with name '_execute_command: service ambari-server start''
  timed out after 300 second(s)

Closes-Bug: #1533887
Change-Id: I7c802cefc090c49663fa44b0436f438a806a5c9d

The OpenStack LLC copyrights date from before OpenStack was transferred

so at least should reflect the correct entity.
